To do this, we can use a simple algorithm that compares each element in one array to each element in the other array. If an element is found in both arrays, we can mark it as a common element.

Here's an example of how this algorithm could be implemented in JavaScript:
```
function findCommonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  const commonElements = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < arr2.length; j++) {
      if (arr1[i] === arr2[j]) {
        commonElements.push(arr1[i]);
      }
    }
  }

  return commonElements;
}
```
This algorithm has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the shorter array. It's a simple and efficient way to find the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures.

